-- Limit Theorems (CredTT-Native #8)
--
-- NEW: Asymptotic arguments and uniform convergence patterns
-- Reason about credence in the limit
--
-- Example: As n -> infinity, c(P(n)) -> 1 (or 0, or some limit)

-- Classical: no limits, just true/false
-- CredTT: credence can converge to limits

-- POINTWISE LIMIT:
-- For each n, c(P(n)) defined
-- lim_{n->inf} c(P(n)) = L

-- Example: Confidence in "random walk returns to origin"
-- c(return by step n) increases with n
-- lim_{n->inf} c(return) = 1 (certain in limit)

postulate step_n : return_by_n @ c_n

-- As n -> infinity:
-- c_n -> 1
-- In the limit, definitely returns

-- UNIFORM CONVERGENCE:
-- For all x, c(P(x, n)) -> L(x) uniformly
-- This is STRONGER than pointwise

-- Uniform: for all epsilon, exists N, for all n > N, for all x:
-- |c(P(x, n)) - L(x)| < epsilon

-- Why uniform matters:
-- Can interchange limits and operations
-- Stable properties preserved in limit

-- NON-UNIFORM EXAMPLE:
-- c(P(x, n)) = n / (n + x)
-- For fixed x: lim_{n->inf} = 1
-- But: for x = n, c = n / (n + n) = 0.5 always
-- Not uniform!

-- CONVERGENCE PATTERNS:

-- 1. Exponential convergence: c_n = 1 - 2^{-n}
--    Fast: reaches 0.999 by n = 10

-- 2. Polynomial convergence: c_n = 1 - 1/n
--    Slow: reaches 0.999 by n = 1000

-- 3. Logarithmic convergence: c_n = 1 - 1/log(n)
--    Very slow: reaches 0.999 by n = e^1000

-- 4. No convergence: c_n = 0.5 + 0.5*sin(n)
--    Oscillates forever

-- WHY LIMIT THEOREMS MATTER:
-- Asymptotic behavior of proofs
-- Does credence stabilize or not?
-- How fast does it converge?

-- Example: Monte Carlo estimation
-- After n samples: c(estimate correct) = 1 - 1/sqrt(n)
-- Convergence rate: O(1/sqrt(n))
-- Need n = 10000 for c = 0.99

-- CredTT can express these asymptotic properties
-- Classical logic cannot
